questions.query: How is the project CollabTech?
questions.explanation:
Breadchain Cooperative's Bread Crowdstaking Application is a way for community's like ours to pool capital together and manage the distribution of the collectivized yield towards initiative and projects within the network through a monthly vote. This is essentially a way for multiple entities and individuals to collaborate on the allocation of capital towards shared goals in a democratic fashion.

https://app.breadchain.xyz/governance

You can see through the example of our first completed voting cycle, how a vote goes and how we plan on improving upon the application.

https://breadchain.mirror.xyz/BMIPx1uJozXLoSTY1bBq5ua6X3qS8qZf5rXUC_fKdjo

questions.query: Who's the targeted user group and what's the need/problem being addressed?
questions.explanation: The targeted user group are those who are intimately involved in various kinds of communities that have aligned values and want to collaborate with pooled capital at scale with others. This helps solve the problem of democratically governing and budgeting among groups with shared purposes.

questions.query: How do you ensure value keeps being delivered after the round is over? (How will the project become commercially sustainable or a perennial good? )
questions.explanation: We are programmatically ensure value is delivered through the monthly vote. After the Gitcoin round is done, our monthly votes will continue on.  The revenue generated from those who bake BREAD, our community token, will always be used to push the Breadchain community forward and build more solidarity primitives like the Bread Crowdstaking Application.

questions.query: How long will it take after funding is received to deliver value? (share a high level timeline)
questions.explanation: The funding will immediately deliver value in that it will be used to help pay the wages of the developers, community stewards, and others in the cooperative. This allows them the freedom to work on Breadchain without fear of losing funding.

questions.query: Vision Statement and Impact: Describe the long-term vision of your project and its intended impact on the Optimism and broader Superchain ecosystem, including both qualitative and quantitative benefits
questions.explanation:
The longterm vision of our project is to build applications that help builders continue to deploy innovative public goods applications on Optimism without having too much of a financial burden. This is what we have set out to build and have been chosen by Optimism to do so as described here: https://app.charmverse.io/op-grants/optimistic-crowdstaking-funding-more-builders-on-optimism-8173089535454674

We believe that by taking a modified version of the crowdstaking application that fits the needs of Optimism, we can make a big impact in a reasonable amount of time as we can build on the learning of deploying it elsewhere. The relief of some financial pressure would help builders create more public goods for the ecosystem to enjoy.

questions.query: Initial Strategy: Outline a high-level strategy for how you will achieve your intended impact and key goals for the next 3-6 months
questions.explanation: Our strategy can be seen in the accepted Optimism application we filled out here: https://app.charmverse.io/op-grants/optimistic-crowdstaking-funding-more-builders-on-optimism-8173089535454674

questions.query: Team Expertise: Provide a brief summary on the team’s background and relevant expertise in token engineering and/or OP
questions.explanation:
Our experience and expertise lies in making the connections between the political imaginaries and concepts for post-capitalism and how they translate onto blockchains in a material sense via software. We have proven that we are able to do this through our writing and deployments of applications that reflect bridging the gap from theory to practice.

As Breadchain Cooperative the team has also been accepted in Token Engineering grant rounds in the past for our work on solidarity primitives and on the crowdstaking application.


Our writing on Solidarity Primitives: https://breadchain.mirror.xyz/nwQx4CqPAcwZ5zSNB2_K25N1quOF1NGcKaYcS3S33CA

questions.query: Existing Work: Provide evidence of any existing work, such as prototypes, research papers, or previous projects. If you have already done work within OP/ Superchain, please include that here too
questions.explanation:

questions.query: Returning grantees: If your project has received prior funding from the Token Engineering Grants Program, please describe the impact that funding has had on the project
questions.explanation: The grants received from Token Engineering have so far have helped us to continue our work and improve upon our application. We have been able to finish the voting module of our system which is now live and we have shared our findings and analysis on our blog: https://breadchain.mirror.xyz/BMIPx1uJozXLoSTY1bBq5ua6X3qS8qZf5rXUC_fKdjo

data.text:
Here are some of the accomplishments we’ve had over the past year of building in relative stealth:

- Transitioned and deployed our Crowdstaking App from Polygon to Gnosis Chain (switch to sDAI yield)
- Breadchain Launch Event in Berlin (feat. endorsement from Vitalik)
- Reached **over $500k in TVL**
- Added new projects like Symbiota, Citizen Wallet, and ReFi DAO
- BREAD integration in Citizen Wallet, Dandelion, and Giveth
- Completed over 4 successful voting cycles with no issues **distributing over $30k to projects using a novel mechanism**
- Sponsored 4 different alternative crypto events
- 2nd place in the Gnosis Pay track at the ETH London hackathon
- **Received a 30k OP grant** from Optimism Collective to build our app for OP builders
- Raised thousands for Eth Evacuations during ETH Berlin
- Updated and improved our original UI and branding
- Regular **weekly community calls** featuring guests from Gnosis Chain, Sensorica, Tech Workers Coalition, and more
- Mention in the books Blockchain Radicals, and Kevin Owocki’s Onchain Capital Allocation v2, Other Internet research on solidarity primitives, Coin Telegraph and several podcasts

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the growth of the OSS ecosystem? Please provide specific examples of how your application enhances or expands the current ecosystem.
questions.explanation: Our application offers a clear example of solidarity primitives, - development tools which help to forge solidarity between individuals and collectives. This is a novel primitive that we coined and expanded on with groups like Other Internet who have researched and published articles on the concept. We believe this kind of primitive offers alternatives to financial primitives that can target users that are less concerned with financial speculation and more with supporting their comunities.

questions.query: What features or use cases does your dApp/App present? How is it differentiated?
questions.explanation: Our application is unique in the web3 space in that it allows users to fund their favorite projects without losing any money through donations and democratically decide on how yield is distributed in a scalable way. By running on a monthly cycle, we are able to keep users engaged in the project as well.

questions.query: What are your plans for further development, and how will the grant funds be used to achieve these goals?
questions.explanation: The two main technical features we are building out to expand the app is a liquidity pool token vault so that users can get voting power for giving liquidity to BREAD as well as voting boosts to empower users in the voting cycles beyond holding BREAD but also by contributing to the network in different ways.

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the growth of the OSS ecosystem? Please provide specific examples of how your application enhances or expands the current ecosystem.
questions.explanation:
The Crowdstaking Application contracts are open source and provide a way for anyone who is interested in making a community currency to fork and deploy or modify it for their own needs. This was useful for the team that built the Optimism Builders Dollar which gives funding to Optimism public goods builders (https://op-builder-dollar.vercel.app/). It has also been useful for a European Commission funded project we have begun for a Serbian artists' cooperative to create their own community currency.

It was also used by Citizen Wallet when designing their community currency project for the city of Brussels.

questions.query: What features or use cases does your dApp/App present? How is it differentiated?
questions.explanation: The Crowdstaking App is unique in its feature set which no other app on the market for governance has offered users. It is designed to have solidarity built in to the voting system and ensures that all projects receive funding. It also takes advantage of allowing users to provide liquidity while still maintaining their voting power. There is also a mobile application through Citizen Wallet that allows users to send and receive BREAD and soon users will be able to vote from their mobile device.

Below is our roadmap with our plans for future features. The funds will help us pay for the labor needed in order to achieve what we have in mind.
